---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const year = new Date().getFullYear();

const meta = [
  { label: 'Role', value: 'Solo Product Designer & Developer' },
  { label: 'Timeline', value: '2024–2025' },
  { label: 'Platform', value: 'iOS (Live on the App Store)' },
];

const alternatives = [
  {
    method: 'Instagram grid/stories',
    strengths: 'Visual, social proof',
    weaknesses: 'Not searchable, stories expire, no setlist data',
  },
  {
    method: 'Notes app',
    strengths: 'Quick, always available',
    weaknesses: 'No structure, no photos, hard to browse',
  },
  {
    method: 'Spreadsheets',
    strengths: 'Structured, sortable',
    weaknesses: 'Ugly, no emotional connection, no images',
  },
  {
    method: 'Setlist.fm',
    strengths: 'Great setlist data',
    weaknesses: 'Not a personal journal, community-focused not me-focused',
  },
  {
    method: 'Memory alone',
    strengths: 'Zero effort',
    weaknesses: 'Unreliable — details fade fast',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Gigz — A Concert Journaling App for Music Fans · Josh Illichmann"
  description="Case study: designing and building Gigz, an iOS concert journaling app for music fans. Card-based timeline, setlist integration, photo personalisation."
>
  <main class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6 overflow-x-hidden">
    <div class="space-y-12 py-12 animate-fade-in-up">
      <!-- Back link + profile -->
      <div class="space-y-6">
        <a
          href="/"
          class="text-sm font-mono text-gray-600 hover:text-gray-900 transition-colors inline-flex items-center gap-2"
        >
          ← BACK
        </a>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3">
          <img
            src="/gigz-icon.png"
            alt="Gigz"
            width="40"
            height="40"
            class="rounded-lg"
          />
          <span class="text-sm font-mono text-gray-600 uppercase">Case Study</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Hero -->
      <header class="space-y-6">
        <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-medium font-mono leading-tight">
          Gigz — A Concert Journaling App for Music Fans
        </h1>
        <p class="text-gray-600 text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
          How do you help music fans preserve and revisit their concert history —
          without making it feel like a chore?
        </p>

        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-3 gap-6 pt-4 text-sm">
          {
            meta.map((item) => (
              <div class="space-y-1">
                <h2 class="font-medium uppercase font-mono text-xs">{item.label}</h2>
                <p class="text-gray-600">{item.value}</p>
              </div>
            ))
          }
        </div>
      </header>

      <!-- Hero image -->
      <div class="bg-gray-100 rounded-xl overflow-hidden">
        <img
          src="/gigz-mock-1.png"
          alt="Gigz iOS app mockup"
          class="w-full h-auto object-cover"
        />
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- The Problem -->
    <section class="py-12">
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 md:gap-14">
        <div class="col-span-1 md:col-span-2">
          <h2 class="text-sm font-mono">THE PROBLEM</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="col-span-1 md:col-span-10 space-y-4 text-base text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            Music fans go to dozens, sometimes hundreds of shows over their lifetime.
            But most have no good way to remember them.
          </p>
          <p>
            Think about it — what was that band you saw at The Corner Hotel in 2008?
            Who opened for them? What songs did they play? What did it feel like?
          </p>
          <p>
            Right now, people cobble together workarounds: scrolling through old
            Instagram posts, saving Stories to highlights, keeping scattered notes in
            their phone, or maintaining spreadsheets. None of these are designed for
            the job. They&apos;re fragile, disconnected, and they don&apos;t capture the
            richness of a live music experience.
          </p>
          <p>I wanted to build something that did.</p>
          <p>
            <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">The insight was twofold:</span>{' '}
            this started as a personal pain point — I&apos;m getting older and didn&apos;t
            want to forget the shows from my early years — but the more I looked into
            it, the more I saw a gap. There was no dedicated, thoughtfully designed
            tool for concert journaling that treated the experience with the care it
            deserved.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Research -->
    <section class="py-12">
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 md:gap-14">
        <div class="col-span-1 md:col-span-2">
          <h2 class="text-sm font-mono">RESEARCH</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="col-span-1 md:col-span-10 space-y-6 text-base text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            It started as my own pain point — but I didn&apos;t want to design for an
            audience of one. Before committing to a direction, I did two kinds of
            lightweight research to pressure-test the idea against real people.
          </p>
          <div class="space-y-2">
            <h3 class="text-gray-900 font-medium">1:1 conversations with concert-goers</h3>
            <p>
              I ran informal interviews with friends and acquaintances across the
              spectrum — from once-a-year casuals to people with decades of shows
              behind them. I wasn&apos;t pitching an app; I asked how they remember
              shows today, what they wish they could look back on, and where their
              current workarounds let them down.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="space-y-2">
            <h3 class="text-gray-900 font-medium">Listening to the wider community</h3>
            <p>
              I spent time in music forums, subreddits, and the App Store reviews of
              adjacent apps to learn the language fans actually use and the gaps they
              complain about — so the product would speak their vocabulary, not mine.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="space-y-3">
            <h3 class="text-gray-900 font-medium">What I heard</h3>
            <ul class="space-y-2 list-disc pl-5">
              <li>
                People remember{' '}
                <span class="text-gray-900">feelings and moments</span> — the photo,
                the support act, that one song — far more vividly than dates and
                venues.
              </li>
              <li>
                Almost everyone had a{' '}
                <span class="text-gray-900">&ldquo;lost history&rdquo; regret</span>{' '}
                — early shows they could no longer reconstruct.
              </li>
              <li>
                Existing workarounds (Instagram, Notes, spreadsheets) were described
                as effort, not joy.
              </li>
              <li>
                Setlists came up again and again as the detail that snaps a memory
                back into focus.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <p>
            <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">How it shaped the design:</span>{' '}
            these findings defined the two user types below, pushed me toward a visual
            card-based timeline rather than a list, and made photos and setlists
            first-class features rather than afterthoughts.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Target Users -->
    <section class="py-12">
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 md:gap-14">
        <div class="col-span-1 md:col-span-2">
          <h2 class="text-sm font-mono">TARGET USERS</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="col-span-1 md:col-span-10 space-y-6 text-base text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          <p>The interviews surfaced two overlapping groups:</p>
          <div class="space-y-4">
            <div class="space-y-2">
              <h3 class="text-gray-900 font-medium">The Nostalgic Fan</h3>
              <p>
                Someone who&apos;s been going to gigs for years or decades and wants
                a way to look back. They might remember the headliner but not the
                support act, the venue but not the date. They want to reconstruct
                and preserve their concert history.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="space-y-2">
              <h3 class="text-gray-900 font-medium">The Active Tracker</h3>
              <p>
                Someone who goes to shows regularly and wants to log them as they
                happen. They care about setlists, venues, and building a visual
                record of their music life over time.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p>
            Both groups share a common need: a single, beautiful place to keep their
            concert memories — something that feels more intentional than a notes
            app and more personal than a social feed.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Existing Alternatives -->
    <section class="py-12">
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 md:gap-14">
        <div class="col-span-1 md:col-span-2">
          <h2 class="text-sm font-mono">LANDSCAPE</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="col-span-1 md:col-span-10 space-y-6 text-base text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            Before designing, I mapped how people were currently solving this
            problem:
          </p>

          <div class="overflow-x-auto -mx-6 px-6">
            <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse min-w-[600px]">
              <thead>
                <tr class="border-b border-gray-200">
                  <th class="text-left py-3 pr-4 font-mono uppercase text-xs text-gray-900 font-medium">
                    Method
                  </th>
                  <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-mono uppercase text-xs text-gray-900 font-medium">
                    Strengths
                  </th>
                  <th class="text-left py-3 pl-4 font-mono uppercase text-xs text-gray-900 font-medium">
                    Weaknesses
                  </th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                {
                  alternatives.map((row) => (
                    <tr class="border-b border-gray-100 align-top">
                      <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-gray-900 font-medium">
                        {row.method}
                      </td>
                      <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600">{row.strengths}</td>
                      <td class="py-3 pl-4 text-gray-600">{row.weaknesses}</td>
                    </tr>
                  ))
                }
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <p>
            The key gap: nothing combined{' '}
            <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">personal journaling</span>{' '}
            (my photos, my memories) with{' '}
            <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">structured music data</span>{' '}
            (setlists, venues, dates) in a way that was easy to use and beautiful
            to look through.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Design Process -->
    <section class="py-12">
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 md:gap-14">
        <div class="col-span-1 md:col-span-2">
          <h2 class="text-sm font-mono">DESIGN PROCESS</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="col-span-1 md:col-span-10 space-y-10 text-base text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          <div class="space-y-4">
            <h3 class="text-gray-900 font-medium text-lg">Information architecture</h3>
            <p>
              The core question was: what&apos;s the right mental model for a
              concert journal?
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-2 list-disc pl-5">
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900">List-based</span> (like a notes app) —
                too utilitarian, no visual delight
              </li>
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900">Calendar-based</span> — good for active
                trackers but bad for retroactive logging
              </li>
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900">Card-based timeline</span> — visual,
                scannable, grouped naturally by time
              </li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              I landed on{' '}
              <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">
                a card-based timeline grouped by year
              </span>
              . Each card shows the artist, venue, date, and a cover photo —
              giving users an immediate visual anchor for each memory.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="space-y-4">
            <h3 class="text-gray-900 font-medium text-lg">The timeline scaling challenge</h3>
            <p>This was the biggest design challenge in the project.</p>
            <p>
              A card-based timeline works beautifully when someone has logged 10–20
              shows. But what happens when a power user has logged 200+ shows
              across 15 years?
            </p>
            <p>
              <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">The problem:</span> If every
              show gets a full-size card regardless of volume, users with rich
              histories would face endless scrolling. But if cards are too
              compressed, you lose the visual impact that makes the journal feel
              personal.
            </p>
            <p>
              <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">My approach:</span> adaptive
              card density thresholds based on the number of shows within a year
              grouping:
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-2 list-disc pl-5">
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900">Low volume (1–5 shows/year):</span>{' '}
                Full-size cards with large cover photos — maximise the visual
                storytelling
              </li>
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900">Medium volume (6–15 shows/year):</span>{' '}
                Compact cards with smaller images — still visually rich but more
                scannable
              </li>
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900">High volume (16+ shows/year):</span>{' '}
                Condensed list-style entries within the year group — prioritise
                browsability, with the option to expand
              </li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              This meant the timeline could scale naturally. Someone logging their
              first year of gigs gets a rich, photo-forward experience. A veteran
              who&apos;s been to 300 shows gets something they can actually
              navigate.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="space-y-4">
            <h3 class="text-gray-900 font-medium text-lg">Setlist integration</h3>
            <p>
              Setlists are a huge part of the concert memory — hearing that one
              song live is often the defining moment. I integrated setlist data so
              users could see (or add) what was played at each show.
            </p>
            <p>
              The challenge here was data quality. Setlist APIs (Setlist.fm) have
              great coverage for major acts but patchy data for smaller venues and
              local scenes. I designed the feature so that:
            </p>
            <ol class="space-y-2 list-decimal pl-5">
              <li>Setlist data auto-populates when available</li>
              <li>Users can manually add or edit setlists when it&apos;s missing</li>
              <li>
                The UI doesn&apos;t feel broken or empty when there&apos;s no
                setlist — it gracefully degrades
              </li>
            </ol>
          </div>

          <div class="space-y-4">
            <h3 class="text-gray-900 font-medium text-lg">
              Photo management & cover personalisation
            </h3>
            <p>
              Users can upload photos for each concert — up to 5 per show. This
              limit was a deliberate constraint driven by storage costs, but I
              framed it as a design choice: it encourages users to pick their
              best, most meaningful photos rather than dumping their entire camera
              roll.
            </p>
            <p>
              A key personalisation feature: users can choose which photo becomes
              the <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">cover image</span> for a
              show&apos;s card in the timeline. This means two users who attended
              the same concert will have completely different-looking journals.
              The cover photo transforms the card from &ldquo;I went to this
              show&rdquo; to &ldquo;this is MY memory of this show.&rdquo;
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Usability Testing -->
    <section class="py-12">
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 md:gap-14">
        <div class="col-span-1 md:col-span-2">
          <h2 class="text-sm font-mono">TESTING</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="col-span-1 md:col-span-10 space-y-6 text-base text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            I tested Gigz continuously rather than in one big round: informal sessions
            with friends and family watching them add their very first show, and
            several TestFlight builds put in front of real users who lived with the app
            over time.
          </p>
          <div class="space-y-2">
            <h3 class="text-gray-900 font-medium">What I watched for</h3>
            <p>
              Could someone log their first concert without any instruction? Where did
              they hesitate? What did they expect to tap that wasn&apos;t there? I paid
              less attention to what people said and more to where they got stuck.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="space-y-4">
            <h3 class="text-gray-900 font-medium">What testing changed</h3>
            <p>
              The most important finding was an authentication failure I&apos;d never
              have caught on my own devices:
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-2 list-disc pl-5">
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">Original design:</span>{' '}
                Sign in with Apple + a one-time code via SMS.
              </li>
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">Problem discovered:</span>{' '}
                some testers on certain carriers silently never received the SMS codes.
                This was a hard blocker — they literally couldn&apos;t get into the
                app, and most wouldn&apos;t have reported it; they&apos;d have just
                left.
              </li>
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">Decision:</span> I removed SMS
                OTP entirely and switched to email-based codes. Less flashy, but
                universally reliable.
              </li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">The lesson:</span> don&apos;t let
              a &ldquo;nice to have&rdquo; auth method create a &ldquo;can&apos;t get
              in&rdquo; experience. Beyond auth, testing reinforced two bets: the card
              timeline genuinely delighted people on first scroll, and retroactive
              logging had to be near-frictionless — confirming the design choices the
              rest of this case study is built on.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Accessibility -->
    <section class="py-12">
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 md:gap-14">
        <div class="col-span-1 md:col-span-2">
          <h2 class="text-sm font-mono">ACCESSIBILITY</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="col-span-1 md:col-span-10 space-y-6 text-base text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            I built Gigz to be a good iOS citizen from the start, and I treat
            accessibility as an ongoing craft rather than a box to tick.
          </p>
          <div class="space-y-2">
            <h3 class="text-gray-900 font-medium">What I addressed</h3>
            <ul class="space-y-2 list-disc pl-5">
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">Touch targets:</span> sized
                interactive elements to comfortable minimums so the app works
                one-handed and forgives less precise taps.
              </li>
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">Dynamic Type:</span> text
                respects the user&apos;s system text-size setting, so the timeline
                stays legible for people who run larger fonts.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="space-y-2">
            <h3 class="text-gray-900 font-medium">What I&apos;m still improving</h3>
            <p>
              A full VoiceOver pass, a formal contrast audit across photo-backed cards,
              and a WCAG-style review are next on my list. I&apos;d rather be honest
              that accessibility is a craft I&apos;m actively levelling up than claim a
              finished bill of health.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Key Design Decisions -->
    <section class="py-12">
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 md:gap-14">
        <div class="col-span-1 md:col-span-2">
          <h2 class="text-sm font-mono">DECISIONS</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="col-span-1 md:col-span-10 space-y-8 text-base text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          <div class="space-y-4">
            <h3 class="text-gray-900 font-medium text-lg">What I built</h3>
            <ul class="space-y-2 list-disc pl-5">
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">
                  Concert journaling with card-based timeline
                </span>{' '}
                — the core experience, grouped by year with adaptive density
              </li>
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">
                  Setlist tracking & integration
                </span>{' '}
                — auto-populated where possible, manually editable where not
              </li>
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">
                  Photo uploads with cover photo personalisation
                </span>{' '}
                — up to 5 photos per show, user-selected cover
              </li>
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">Venue database & search</span>{' '}
                — powered by multiple APIs (MusicBrainz, OpenStreetMap) for
                comprehensive coverage
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="space-y-4">
            <h3 class="text-gray-900 font-medium text-lg">What I intentionally left out</h3>
            <ul class="space-y-2 list-disc pl-5">
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">Social features</span> —
                No sharing, no friends list, no public profiles. A deliberate V1
                scoping decision. The journaling experience needed to be solid
                before adding social layers. Adding social too early risks turning
                a personal journal into a performance.
              </li>
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">
                  Discovery / recommendations
                </span>{' '}
                — The app is about YOUR history, not suggesting new shows. Scope
                control.
              </li>
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">
                  Unlimited photo uploads
                </span>{' '}
                — Capped at 5 per show for storage cost management, but also
                because constraints often improve the end result.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Outcomes & Reflections -->
    <section class="py-12">
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 md:gap-14">
        <div class="col-span-1 md:col-span-2">
          <h2 class="text-sm font-mono">OUTCOMES</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="col-span-1 md:col-span-10 space-y-8 text-base text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          <div class="space-y-4">
            <h3 class="text-gray-900 font-medium text-lg">What shipped</h3>
            <p>
              Gigz is{' '}
              <a
                href="https://gigz.app"
                target="_blank"
                rel="noopener noreferrer"
                class="text-gray-900 font-medium underline"
              >
                live on the App Store
              </a>{' '}
              — a fully functional concert journaling app that lets music fans
              log, revisit, and personalise their concert history.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="space-y-4">
            <h3 class="text-gray-900 font-medium text-lg">What I learned</h3>
            <ul class="space-y-3 list-disc pl-5">
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">
                  Constraints are design tools.
                </span>{' '}
                The 5-photo limit and the decision to cut social features
                weren&apos;t just cost-saving measures — they sharpened the
                product&apos;s identity. Gigz is a personal journal, and every
                decision reinforced that.
              </li>
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">
                  Test authentication early and broadly.
                </span>{' '}
                The SMS OTP issue could have been a launch blocker if I
                hadn&apos;t caught it in TestFlight. Auth is infrastructure, but
                it&apos;s also a UX surface.
              </li>
              <li>
                <span class="text-gray-900 font-medium">
                  Scaling UX matters from day one.
                </span>{' '}
                The timeline density challenge wasn&apos;t a &ldquo;nice to
                have&rdquo; — it was the difference between an app that works for
                casual users and one that works for everyone.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="space-y-4">
            <h3 class="text-gray-900 font-medium text-lg">What&apos;s next</h3>
            <ul class="space-y-2 list-disc pl-5">
              <li>
                Exploring social features (sharing individual show cards, comparing
                concert history with friends)
              </li>
              <li>
                Richer data visualisation (concert stats, venue maps, genre
                breakdowns over time)
              </li>
              <li>Expanded venue and artist database coverage</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Process Artifacts -->
    <section class="py-12">
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 md:gap-14">
        <div class="col-span-1 md:col-span-2">
          <h2 class="text-sm font-mono">ARTIFACTS</h2>
        </div>
